Abstract
In this work, we present a numerical treatment for the model of two-phase ï¬‚ow in porous
media including speciï¬c interfacial area. For numerical discretization we use the cell-centered
ï¬nite diï¬€erence (CCFD) method based on the shifting-matrices method which can reduce the
time-consuming operations. A new iterative implicit algorithm has been developed to solve the
problem under consideration. All advection and advection-like terms that appear in saturation
equation and interfacial area equation are treated using upwind schemes. Selected simulation
results such as pc âˆ’ Sw âˆ’ awn surface, capillary pressure, saturation and speciï¬c interfacial area
with various values of model parameters have been introduced. The simulation results show a
good agreement with those in the literature using either pore network modeling or Darcy scale
modeling.
Keywords: Interfacial area, Two-phase ï¬‚ow, Porous media, Capillary pressure, CCFD method, Shiftingmatrices method

1

Introduction

The model of ï¬‚ow and transport in porous media, Darcyâ€™s law, was originally proposed empirically for one-dimensional isothermal ï¬‚ow of an incompressible ï¬‚uid in a rigid, homogeneous
and isotropic porous medium. The extended Darcyâ€™s Law is used for highly complex situations
like non-isothermal, multiphase and multicomponent ï¬‚ow and transport, without introducing
any additional driving forces. The resisting force, which balances the driving force, is assumed
to be linearly proportional to the relative ï¬‚uid velocity with respect to the solid. This results
in a linear relationship between the ï¬‚ow velocity and driving forces. While these assumptions
are reasonable for single-phase ï¬‚ow, one may expect many other factors to aï¬€ect the balance of
forces in the case of multiphase ï¬‚ow. Hassanizadeh and Gray [7, 8] developed a uniï¬ed model
âˆ— Corresponding

Author

Selection and peer-review under responsibility of the Scientiï¬c Programme Committee of ICCS 2015
