based on rational thermodynamics leading to additional driving forces. The macroscale eï¬€ects
of interfacial forces were included and the momentum balance equations are derived for both
phases and interfaces. They found that the driving forces for the ï¬‚ow of a phase were the gradients of Gibbs free energy of the phase plus gravity. In the case of single-phase ï¬‚ow, the gradient
of Gibbs free energy reduces to the gradient of pressure. Moreover, capillary pressure is not a
hysteretic function of saturation only, but uniquely deï¬ned by a capillary pressure-saturationspeciï¬c interfacial area surface. In Hassanizadeh and Gray [7], the equations constitute a very
complex model that includes many diï¬€erent eï¬€ects. However, some of these eï¬€ects are being of
second order, whereas several of the involved constitutive relationships have not been investigated so far. In Hassanizadeh and Gray [8], the momentum balance equations were simpliï¬ed.
These studies were followed by a number of other studies (e.g. [9, 10]). Most of these works
were done using poreâ€“network modeling and/or experiments and very few attempts were done
to simulate the macroscale multiphase ï¬‚ow model including the speciï¬c interfacial area such
as Ref. [17]. The IMplicit Pressure Explicit Saturation (IMPES) approach solves the pressure equation implicitly and updates the saturation explicitly. In IMPES method, the time
step size should be very small, in particular, for highly heterogeneous permeable media. Because the decoupling between the pressure equation and the saturation equation, the IMPES
method is conditionally stable. Iterative IMPES splits the equation system into a pressure and
a saturation equation that are solved sequentially as IMPES [14, 15, 13].
The objective of this work is to develop an accurate numerical simulator for two-phase ï¬‚ow
in porous media including speciï¬c interfacial area using appropriate numerical methods. The
cell-centered ï¬nite diï¬€erence (CCFD) method together with the shifting-matrices approach are
used for spacial discretization, while the upwind scheme is used to treat the advection terms in
the diï¬€erential system.

2

Modeling and Mathematical Formulation

Hassanizadeh and Gray [7] have used a thermodynamic approach using the concept of Gibbs
free energy. They concluded that the movement of each phase or interface is governed by its
gradient in Gibbs free energy. Now, let us consider the ï¬‚ow of two immiscible and compressible
ï¬‚uids including interfacial area. Assuming that the porosity is constant; the interfacial mass
density is constant; the gravity does not have eï¬€ect on interfacial movement; all material
properties are neglected; mass exchange between phases and interfaces has negligible eï¬€ect on
mass balance of phases; and the cross-coupling terms are negligible. Therefore, the governing
equations describing the above system can be written as follows [16],
