Numerical Experiments

This section analyzes some results of saturation, capillary pressure and speciï¬c interfacial area.
For example, we choose ï¬‚uid parameters (densities, viscosities, and diï¬€usion constants) of water and air; for the matrix parameters, we take typical soil parameters, here k = 10âˆ’10 m2 and
Ï† = 0.3. We take a rough estimate of knw = 10âˆ’5 m3 sâˆ’1 . We set the interfacial permeability Kwn to 10âˆ’5 m3 /s. The ratio between non-wetting phase and wetting-phase viscosity is
Î¼n /Î¼w = 0.1. The coeï¬ƒcients for the production rate of speciï¬c interfacial area we use the
values from Ref. [10]. The initial condition for the speciï¬c interfacial awn is taken as 5790 [1/m]
and at the boundary conditions are given as: 1000 [1/m] on the west boundary; 5790 [1/m]
on the east boundary; and 0 [1/m] on the north and south boundary. Also, the boundary
conditions of the interface velocity vwn , is considered 0.001 [m/year] on the west boundary and
0 [m/year] on the east, north and south boundaries. The parameters in the capillary pressure
formula are set to Î±1 = 250 000, Î±2 = 1.18 and Î±3 = âˆ’0.8. Figure 1 represents relation between speciï¬c interfacial area, saturation and capillary pressure. It is interesting to note that
this 3D surface is comparable to previous experimental and computational studies, [1, 10, 18].
Figure 2(a) shows the variation of capillary pressure with saturation. From this ï¬gure we may
conclude that the capillary pressure increases with decreasing wetting-phase saturation. The
variations of the speciï¬c interfacial area with wetting-phase saturation are plotted in Fig. 2(b).
According to this ï¬gure, one can observe that the speciï¬c interfacial area decreases with increasing the wetting-phase saturation.
In another example, we choose counter-current imbibition model [3, 4, 5, 6, 2]. In the case
of considering the speciï¬câ€“interfacialâ€“area, the capillary pressure formula pc (Sw , awn ) is very
sensitive to its parameters. The values of these parameters may be modiï¬ed based on the type
of porous media and other physical and computational aspects. So, here we investigate the
sensitivity of the capillary pressure parameters, namely, Î±1 , Î±2 and Î±3 . In Fig. 3a, the speciï¬c
interfacial area is plotted against the capillary pressure with diï¬€erent values of Î±1 , at Î±2 = 1.18
and Î±3 = âˆ’0.8. This ï¬gure shows that the speciï¬c interfacial area could has same values for
diï¬€erent capillary pressure ranges based on the values of the parameter Î±1 . Fig. 3b shows
the speciï¬c interfacial area proï¬les against the capillary pressure with various values of the
parameter Î±2 , at Î±1 = 2.5 Ã— 107 and Î±3 = âˆ’0.8. It is interesting to note from Fig. 3b that the
behavior of the interfacial area proï¬les with small values of Î±2 is totally diï¬€erent from those
with bigger values of Î±2 . The speciï¬c interfacial area decreases as the parameter Î±2 decreases
and opposite is true for the capillary pressure. The speciï¬c interfacial area is plotted in Fig. 3c
against the capillary pressure with diï¬€erent values of Î±3 , at Î±1 = 2.5 Ã— 107 and Î±2 = 1.18.
It can be seen from this ï¬gure that as the parameter Î±3 increases the interfacial area slightly
increases with bigger values of the capillary pressure. Also, Fig. Fig. 3c illustrates the capillary
pressure variation against the water saturation at diï¬€erent values of Î±1 , at Î±2 = 1.18 and
Î±3 = âˆ’0.8. It is clear from this ï¬gure that as the parameter Î±1 increases the capillary pressure
increases. Moreover, it is interesting to note from the same ï¬gure that the capillary pressure
has reasonable physical values of Î±1 â‰¥ o(105 ). The proï¬les of the capillary pressure are plotted
in Fig. 3d against the water saturation with diï¬€erent values of the parameter Î±2 = 0.01 : 2.5, at
Î±1 = 2.5Ã—107 and Î±3 = âˆ’0.8. It is clear here that when Î±2 > 1, the behavior of the Pc âˆ’S curve
deviates from the standard behavior. Fig. 3e shows the capillary pressure against the water
saturation with diï¬€erent values of the Î±3 , with Î±1 = 2.5 Ã— 107 and Î±2 = 1.18. From Fig. 3f,
it can be noted that the behavior of the Pc âˆ’ S curve deviates from the standard behavior at
Î±3 > âˆ’0.8.
